==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|pedant|lang=frm}}, {{term|pedante|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|it|en}} {{term|lang=it|pedante||a teacher, schoolmaster, pedant}}, of uncertain origin, traced by some sources<!--Century 1911, Online Etymology Dictionary--> to Latin {{term|paedagogans|lang=la}}, present participle of paedagogare ( = to teach, from Greek "paedagogein" = to instruct children ). Confer French {{term|pédant|lang=fr}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|pĕdʹənt}}, {{IPA|/ˈpɛdənt/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"pEd@nt/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[teacher]] or [[schoolmaster]].
#* '''1603''', John Florio, translating Michel de Montaigne, ''Essays'', vol. 1 ch. 24:
#*: I have in my youth oftentimes beene vexed to see a '''Pedant''' [''tr. [[pedante]]''] brought in, in most of Italian comedies, for a vice or sport-maker, and the nicke-name of ''Magister'' to be of no better signification amongst us.
# A person who is overly concerned with formal rules and trivial points of learning.
# A person who emphasizes his/her knowledge through the use of vocabulary.

